I recently had to test an api with a popular app called
[[https://www.postman.com/][PostMan]] but did not like that it kept
reminding me how limited the freemium version was. Not to mention the
unsolicited "AI assistance" features. So I set out to make some notes on
a free and possibly better alternative: [[https://curl.se/][Curl]] .
This is an early version of those notes.

I'll only focus on the
[[https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Guides/Overview][http
protocol]] for this article (and will consider add notes for others when
my need for using curl with them arises) but I'm sure that's for most,
all they ever get to use with curl.

So what is curl?

It's a very old (26 years as of when I am writing this) popular cli tool
for network data transfer by Daniel Stenberg.

All its file-transfer functionality is powered by an underlying library
called libcurl.

The 'c' in Curl is for 'client' since it is a client side tool and the
URL is because its a tool for 'downloading and uploading data with a
url'. Okay, enough trivia.

Curl comes preinstalled on most linux distros but if it ain't installed
you can install it using your distro's package manager. I am running
Arch so that would be:

#+begin_src sh
pacman -S curl
#+end_src

